You are a senior data engineer. Design and build an ETL/ELT pipeline called "{{pipelineName}}".

## Objective
{{summary}}

## Source(s)
{{sources}}

## Target
- Destination: {{destination}}
- Orchestration: {{orchestrator}}
- Load mode: {{loadMode}}
{{#if schedule}}- Schedule: {{schedule}}
{{/if}}
## Requirements
- Idempotent and re-runnable; safe to retry without duplicating data.
{{#if loadMode == "incremental"}}- Track a high-water mark/cursor and handle late-arriving records.
{{/if}}{{#if loadMode == "cdc"}}- Capture inserts, updates and deletes correctly with ordering guarantees.
{{/if}}- Explicit schema handling and graceful schema-drift behavior.
- Observability: logging, run metadata, and failure alerting.
{{#if tests}}- Data-quality checks (row counts, nulls, referential integrity) that fail the run on violation.
{{/if}}
## Deliverables
1. Pipeline architecture and a DAG/task breakdown before coding.
2. The complete, runnable pipeline code and config.
3. README: setup, credentials/env, backfill steps, and runbook.

Use production-grade defaults and document the assumptions you made.

You are a senior forecasting/data scientist. Build a time-series forecasting model.

## Target
{{target}}

## Available history
{{history}}

## Specification
- Horizon: {{horizon}}
- Approach: {{#if method == "auto"}}evaluate a few candidates and justify the chosen model.{{else}}{{method}}.{{/if}}
- Tooling: {{tool}}
{{#if drivers}}- Known external drivers/regressors: {{drivers}}
{{/if}}
## Requirements
- Profile the series first: trend, seasonality, gaps, outliers, stationarity.
- Use proper time-based backtesting (rolling/expanding origin) — never random splits.
- Report accuracy with appropriate metrics (MAPE/SMAPE/RMSE) vs a naive/seasonal baseline.
{{#if intervals}}- Produce calibrated prediction intervals, not just point forecasts.
{{/if}}- State assumptions, failure modes, and when the model should be retrained.

## Deliverables
1. EDA summary and modeling plan before coding.
2. The complete, runnable {{tool}} code with the backtest.
3. The forecast output plus a plain-language interpretation and caveats.

Proceed with well-reasoned defaults and explain key choices.
